  dcterms:identifier "zotero:6479329:SGTLPMI4" ;
  schema:description "The demand for cheap labor and the use of people for exploitation are not new and have been part of societal norms for many centuries.Over the past 200 years, international legal instruments and domestic legislation have been introduced to suppress and criminalize slavery, forced labor and human trafficking.Taking many different forms, from the trafficking of human organs to forcing children to sell drugs, there is often confusion, disagreement and even disbelief that these crimes exist.In 1927, the Slavery Convention, and in 1930, the Forced Labour Convention began the global campaign to prohibit slavery, forced labor and forms of human trafficking across the world.The Universal Declaration of Human Rights reinforces protections from slavery and forced labour, as do conventions, directives and protocols of the Council of Europe, the European Union (EU), and the United Nations (UN).Despite all these measures, the prevalence of human trafficking is increasing, the identification of victims is below one percent, and the sanction of perpetrators is in decline.Often conflated with people smuggling, human trafficking does not require the crossing of a border or the movement of a person.As a serious crime, it can involve threats, abuse of a position of authority, coercion or violence.And just like other crimes involving violence and exploitation, criminals identify a vulnerability to control their victim.The root causes of human trafficking are many and complex.Displacement, poverty, inequality, corruption, businesses flouting laws, demand and greed are just some of the reasons why people are trafficked and exploited.But human trafficking is never inevitable.It is a serious crime in which a person or persons decide to exploit a child, woman or man, and in most cases, to make money.It is a serious violation of human rights, and people's rights must be protected.But until human trafficking is recognized as a deliberate act by people, responses and prevention will remain passive and unable to hold those who are responsible, including governments and businesses, to account.Changing the paradigm from an annual US$150 billion criminal profit going untraced while only viii FOREWORD one in every 8700 victims sees a perpetrator convicted, to one of no profit and a likelihood of prosecution will take determined efforts and strong leadership.Short-term projects, inadequate budgets and victim-blaming have become synonymous with government responses to trafficking.A continued assertion that it is nearly impossible to investigate these crimes as victims do not cooperate is untrue.It gives traffickers confidence in impunity, something they should never be afforded.International instruments have been very clear and call on states to investigate human trafficking, even when a victim does not cooperate or give consent.Some states' responses are improving, introducing action plans, legislation to support victims, and independent oversight.But even then, often, the response does not fit the crime.This book, which draws on the experience of experts and survivors from across the world, not only explores the different forms of modern slavery and human trafficking but also the root causes, ways to prevent exploitation, victim support and investigation techniques.With such wide-ranging expertise, this book provides an unrivaled and unique reference for policymakers and those who want to understand the true impact this crime has on those whom it affects the most: the victims.In 2015, UN member states committed to achieving a better world by adopting the Sustainable Development Goals or SDGs.SDG 8.7 commits to eradicating modern slavery, human trafficking, forced labor and child labor.The chapters of this book contain many of the answers to achieving the ambitious SDG 8.7.By 2024, no one should be the victim of modern slavery or human trafficking.Implementing effective solutions is well overdue.This book will act as a catalyst to finding those solutions, with gratitude to the many global contributors." ;
  schema:author "Krambia-Kapardē, Maria ca. 20./21. Jh." ;
